strategy: My decisions were solely based on the amount of alcohol and amount of food present at the event. Usually when hosts of parties have a moderate amount of alcohol and food the event is worth going to. When there was not enough information provided about the amount of alcohol or food provided I based my decisions on the distance from home and the duration of the party. I don't like to go to parties if they are far and will only last for a few minutes. I think that is a waste of time. However, if the party happened to be far in distance and lasted for a few minutes, BUT still provided food and alcohol I would most likely attend.
strategy2: My strategy has not changed, I still would base my choices on an importance factor.
metastrategy: I decided my answer based on an importance factor such as which decision would be more important to me (i.e., having more alcohol at the party of the duration of the party).

I would then look at the amount of time it would take to go to both and weigh in on if it would be worth driving shorter even if I would have to socialize with some people. Then I typically prefer to be outdoors instead of indoors so I would repeat the same process as I did with distance but instead I would ask myself about would I be willing to go to an event with more socializing but be outdoors? or similar questions. Then I would look at other things such as the amount of food, music, the duration, and physical activity as I dont really feel those are deal breakers for me. I would easily go to an event with food just as easy as going to an event with food. Same thing for music, duration, and physical activity.
strategy2: I dont think my strategy changed for the main categories I cared about. But I feel it did change for the ones that I cared for a little. strategy: I weighed each factor in different ways, but it was hard to keep track of how each variable reacts with one another. Another confusing point was that if the other people at the event were people I was more familiar with vs them being strangers, decisions could have been slightly adjusted. Generally though, if there was alcohol without food, that was not the greatest sign. I enjoy alcohol, so that was a plus. Distance didn't matter much to me because I used to travel quite a bit, so that wasn't much of a factor much of the time. If an event had physical exercise, then I would be more apt to pick it. I like socializing as well, especially at events, because that's what events are for, so if a choice did not have any socializing, that was a negative factor.
strategy2: I think my strategy was all over the place now that I am looking at it more critically. If all things were equal, it would be easier to make a decision between two events, but since they were not, factoring in how much something matter was very hard. For example, I don't mind music, but I don't particularly care for it at events. That being said, if socialization was high, I may not want much music, since music may get in the way of socialization. But with a lot of physical exercise, music can be a great option. Therefore, I would describe my strategy as dependent on many intertwining factors that are hard to explain. I'd change my description to essentially become more complex. Although I don't care for music much or the distance from an event as some examples, there are circumstances under which I would care for them.
metastrategy: While going through the process of answering 100 questions in Section 1, I was constantly thinking of how much I cared about the different variables and how they interact with one another vs the other option I had, which helped me answer the questions in Section 2.

He considered the difference between the two events on each feature (e.g. 30 minutes away vs. 10 minutes away = a 20 minute difference in distance from home), and then weighed those differences t
strategy:
The first consideration for me was distance from home - I'm almost always going to prefer the event that's 5 or 15 minutes away to the event that's 55+ minutes away, regardless of other offerings.

If distance is similar, I look next at physical activity. I'm lazy, and not likely to pay to do something that requires a high level of activity. That's what the gym is for, not an event.

Next, I look at food, then music, then alcohol, then the duration of the event. If the distance from home is similar with both, I need it to have at least food or music, and not necessarily alcohol. Events that are far away with lots of alcohol and no food are really bad ideas, so I tried to avoid selecting those. If faced with choosing between two events that are both really far away, I chose the longer event usually - I don't want to drive 55+ minutes for a 30 minute event.
strategy2: I would still describe it similarly - I had a few (many really) key areas that I cared about, but I cared about the items to varying degrees.
metastrategy: I know what my process was because I paid attention and thought through the scenarios and knew what data I was looking for, and in what order. I thought carefully through the selections that weren't clear-cut, and knew why the ones that were clear-cut for me were that way.

strategy: My biggest factors were food, alcohol, and how ability to socialize.  I had a tendency to choose the option that had time to socialize with others, as I find this the most appealing in attending events as I enjoy meeting and speaking with other people.  Food and alcohol took second place for me, especially food, as having food at an event is a big plus for me, and I enjoy events where alcohol is served as well.  The other factors such as time and location didn't play a big role in my choice, as they're not things I'd consider big inconveniences in my real life.  Physical activity factored into my choices a bit, but not to a great degree, as I do not mind being physically active.  Though if I have to be, I prefer it being at an event where I can be social.  As for music, that didn't weigh into much of my decision as I felt music is nice at an event, but not by any means necessary.  The same was indoors or outdoors, as long as the event has a number of things I favored, I did not mind the locating being inside nor outside.
strategy2: My description has not changed, it was exactly how I described it originally.  The only new thing I could say is based upon what I learned in the survey is that I weighed my decisions based upon what I found to be the most important aspects of my decision making in choosing which event to attend.  With that in mind, socialization almost always was the most important of my decision factors, followed by the number of people, and then food along with alcohol.  Length and distance played into my decisions very little as did music.  Outdoors or indoors had little impact as well.  Physical activity had a moderate impact on what I chose.
metastrategy: I based my choices in section 1 based upon my personality, as I know my likes and dislikes when attending events. strategy: I first always looked at the duration of the event and the time it would take to get there. I didn't want to go to an event that took 50 minutes to get to for a 30 minute event, for example, so that ratio was important to me. I also looked at how long the total event would last including event duration + drive to get there and back, to see how much of a total time commitment this would be. After that, I would look at the presence of food and alcohol, then the amount of physical activity. The amount of social interaction and location of the event was a little bit important, but not often or always taken into consideration when making my decision. The number of people at the event was never an important factor for me. Usually, looking at the time of events and the drive, along with the presence of food and drinks, was enough to help me make my decision (i.e. events that are longer than the drive to get there, short drives, not too long events, those which had a decent amount of food and/or alcohol, etc were my top choices)
strategy2: I think my description is still accurate. I weighed each of the factors differently, and not all had importance to me. I checked to see which event "won" each of the factors I found important, but I looked at the combination of these factors together, not always just picking the event that "won" in a specific factor always

He considered the difference between the two events on each feature (e.g. 30 minutes away vs. 10 minutes away = a 20 minute difference in distance from home), and then weighed those differences t
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between events in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: the opportunity to socialize, the amount of food present, and the amount of alcohol present. He checked which event was better on each feature (i.e. which event 'won' on each feature), and chose the event that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
strategy: Eventually I settled on usually looking at the distance from home first and going from there.  I tended to favor events that had both alcohol and social interaction to some degree.  I usually avoided events that had alcohol but no social interaction opportunities as who wants to drive for an hour just to drink alone.  For me, the amount of music at the event was basically a non-factor.  I also found the duration of the event to usually be irrelevant except when it was a choice between the extreme ends of the scale or when the distance from home was high.
strategy2: It hasn't really changed.  My main factors were distance from home, presence of alcohol, availability of social interaction and lack of physical activity.  While I did place a fair amount of importance to having alcohol at the event, it wasn't the only deciding factor.  It was key that, when choosing an event with the alcohol, that there were also social opportunities as well.
metastrategy: Over the course of the 100 event choices, I somewhat went over my thought process as I was doing it.  Over time, I pretty much honed in on the most important factors to me.  I knew there would be some questions about it so I tried to make sure I was aware of how I was making the choices in Section 1.
